<subSubSection id="7CBD6547B565DB786CD7B66EFF27F8C7" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" type="description">
<paragraph id="341836CCB565DB786CD7B66EFF27F8C7" blockId="7.[151,1437,1049,1686]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">
A single male was collected in 2014 on the hilltop flying slowly about two meters from the ground around 17:00h. 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786CD7B64AFE93FA07" box="[151,340,1085,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epaphus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786CD7B64AFE93FA07" box="[151,340,1085,1110]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Mesene epaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a highly variable species (
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB565DB786EF0B649FC61FA07" author="Hall" box="[688,934,1085,1110]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" refString="Hall, J. P. W. &amp; Harvey, D. J. (2002) A survey of androconial organs in the Riodinidae (Lepidoptera). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 136, 171 - 197. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00003. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Hall &amp; Harvey 2002</bibRefCitation>
), with four names proposed to describe its diversity. Three of those names are recognized as valid subspecies (
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB565DB786FECB615FB1CFA2B" author="Callaghan" box="[940,1243,1121,1146]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" refString="Callaghan, C. J. &amp; Lamas, G. (2004) Riodinidae. In: Lamas, G. (Ed.), Checklist: Part 4 A. Hesperioidea-Papilionoidea. In: Heppner, J. B. (Ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera 5 A. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera / Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, pp. 141 - 170." type="book chapter" year="2004">Callaghan &amp; Lamas 2004</bibRefCitation>
): the nominative subspecies, described from 
<collectingCountry id="4CB0765CB565DB786D9DB6F1FDF8FACF" box="[477,575,1157,1182]" name="Suriname" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Surinam</collectingCountry>
, is characterized by the reddish orange ground color of the apex of the forewing upper side (
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB786DDBB6DDFE32FA93" box="[411,501,1193,1218]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1766,1789]" captionTargetBox="[232,1349,195,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[232,1350,195,1734]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in dorsal and ventral views. 1 – 2 M. gracielae sp. nov., male holotype. 3 – 4 M. monostigma monostigma, male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil. 5 – 8 M. nepticula stigmosa, 5 – 6 male; 7 – 8 female. 9 – 12 M. eupteryx stat. rest., 9 – 10 male from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 11 – 12 female. 13 – 14 M. nola, male from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil. 15 – 20 M. paraena, 15 – 16 male from Cáceres, Mato Grosso, Brazil; 17 – 18 male; 19 – 20 female. 21 – 28 M. epaphus (23 – 28 upper side left, underside right), 21 – 22 M. epaphus pyrrha, male; 23 female from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil; 24 female from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 25 M. epaphus epaphus, male from Belém, Pará, Brazil; 26 M. epaphus pyrrha, male from São Paulo de Olivença, Amazonas, Brazil; 27 – 28, M. epaphus pyrrha, males from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil. 29 – 32 M. leucophrys, 29 – 30 male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil; 31 – 32 female. Scale bar 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256291/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786E51B6DEFC57FA93" authority="Bates, 1868" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1868" box="[529,912,1193,1218]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="epaphus" subSpecies="pyrrha">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E51B6DEFD33FA93" box="[529,756,1193,1218]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus pyrrha</emphasis>
Bates, 1868
</taxonomicName>
, described from Tefé, 
<collectingRegion id="F663F82EB565DB7868E5B6DEFAD9FA93" box="[1189,1310,1194,1218]" country="Brazil" name="Amazonas" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="4CB0765CB565DB786970B6DDFAB0FA93" box="[1328,1399,1193,1218]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, is characterized by the black ground color of the apex of the forewing, with white and reddish orange subapical and submarginal spots (
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB786D34B685FDE3FB5B" box="[372,548,1265,1290]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1766,1789]" captionTargetBox="[232,1349,195,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[232,1350,195,1734]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in dorsal and ventral views. 1 – 2 M. gracielae sp. nov., male holotype. 3 – 4 M. monostigma monostigma, male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil. 5 – 8 M. nepticula stigmosa, 5 – 6 male; 7 – 8 female. 9 – 12 M. eupteryx stat. rest., 9 – 10 male from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 11 – 12 female. 13 – 14 M. nola, male from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil. 15 – 20 M. paraena, 15 – 16 male from Cáceres, Mato Grosso, Brazil; 17 – 18 male; 19 – 20 female. 21 – 28 M. epaphus (23 – 28 upper side left, underside right), 21 – 22 M. epaphus pyrrha, male; 23 female from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil; 24 female from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 25 M. epaphus epaphus, male from Belém, Pará, Brazil; 26 M. epaphus pyrrha, male from São Paulo de Olivença, Amazonas, Brazil; 27 – 28, M. epaphus pyrrha, males from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil. 29 – 32 M. leucophrys, 29 – 30 male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil; 31 – 32 female. Scale bar 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256291/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Figs 21–22, 28</figureCitation>
); and 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786E2BB686FC2FFB5B" authority="Stichel, 1910" authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1910" box="[619,1000,1265,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="epaphus" subSpecies="sertata">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E2BB686FC81FB58" box="[619,838,1265,1290]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus sertata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB565DB786F0FB685FC2FFB5B" author="Stichel" box="[847,1000,1265,1290]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" refString="Stichel, H. (1910) Fam. Riodinidae. Allgemeines. Subfam. Riodininae. Genera Insectorum, 112 a, 1 - 238." type="book chapter" year="1910">Stichel, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, also described from Tefé, 
<collectingRegion id="F663F82EB565DB78695FB686FA5FFB5B" box="[1311,1432,1266,1290]" country="Brazil" name="Amazonas" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="4CB0765CB565DB786CD7B761FF19FB7F" box="[151,222,1301,1326]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, is an intermediate between the phenotypes of typical 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786F0CB761FC6EFB7F" box="[844,937,1301,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epaphus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786F0CB761FC6EFB7F" box="[844,937,1301,1326]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">epaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786FA4B761FBF7FB7F" box="[996,1072,1301,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrrha">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786FA4B761FBF7FB7F" box="[996,1072,1301,1326]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">pyrrha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with the forewing apex mostly reddish orange, but with the white subapical spot visible throughout the reddish orange ground color (
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB78694DB74DFA57FB03" box="[1293,1424,1337,1362]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1766,1789]" captionTargetBox="[232,1349,195,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[232,1350,195,1734]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in dorsal and ventral views. 1 – 2 M. gracielae sp. nov., male holotype. 3 – 4 M. monostigma monostigma, male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil. 5 – 8 M. nepticula stigmosa, 5 – 6 male; 7 – 8 female. 9 – 12 M. eupteryx stat. rest., 9 – 10 male from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 11 – 12 female. 13 – 14 M. nola, male from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil. 15 – 20 M. paraena, 15 – 16 male from Cáceres, Mato Grosso, Brazil; 17 – 18 male; 19 – 20 female. 21 – 28 M. epaphus (23 – 28 upper side left, underside right), 21 – 22 M. epaphus pyrrha, male; 23 female from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil; 24 female from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 25 M. epaphus epaphus, male from Belém, Pará, Brazil; 26 M. epaphus pyrrha, male from São Paulo de Olivença, Amazonas, Brazil; 27 – 28, M. epaphus pyrrha, males from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil. 29 – 32 M. leucophrys, 29 – 30 male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil; 31 – 32 female. Scale bar 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256291/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Figs 26–27</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB565DB786CD7B729FE54FB27" author="Hall" box="[151,403,1373,1398]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" refString="Hall, J. P. W. &amp; Harvey, D. J. (2002) A survey of androconial organs in the Riodinidae (Lepidoptera). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 136, 171 - 197. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1096 - 3642.2002.00003. x" type="journal article" year="2002">Hall &amp; Harvey (2002)</bibRefCitation>
downgraded 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786E6EB72AFD66FB27" box="[558,673,1373,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrrha">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E6EB72AFD66FB27" box="[558,673,1373,1398]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. pyrrha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786F3CB72AFBC7FB27" box="[892,1024,1373,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epaphus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786F3CB72AFBC7FB27" box="[892,1024,1373,1398]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and, observing the high variability, suggested that probably no subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786E31B7F6FD32FBCB" box="[625,757,1409,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epaphus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E31B7F6FD32FBCB" box="[625,757,1409,1434]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be recognized. We studied several western Amazon specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786D7DB7D2FE01FBEF" box="[317,454,1445,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epaphus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786D7DB7D2FE01FBEF" box="[317,454,1445,1470]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
deposited at the 
<collectionCode id="52B6AE09B565DB786EDDB7D2FD21FBEC" box="[669,742,1446,1469]" country="Brazil" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/5xp9-edpx" name="Universidade Federal do Parana, Colecao de Entomologia Pe. Jesus Santiago Moure" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">DZUP</collectionCode>
(
<figureCitation id="AC9C2A49B565DB786EBBB7D1FC18FBEF" box="[763,991,1445,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 32" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1766,1789]" captionTargetBox="[232,1349,195,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[232,1350,195,1734]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 32. Mesene species from Parque Nacional da Serra do Divisor, Acre, Brazil (unless otherwise indicated), in dorsal and ventral views. 1 – 2 M. gracielae sp. nov., male holotype. 3 – 4 M. monostigma monostigma, male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil. 5 – 8 M. nepticula stigmosa, 5 – 6 male; 7 – 8 female. 9 – 12 M. eupteryx stat. rest., 9 – 10 male from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 11 – 12 female. 13 – 14 M. nola, male from Alto Alegre, Roraima, Brazil. 15 – 20 M. paraena, 15 – 16 male from Cáceres, Mato Grosso, Brazil; 17 – 18 male; 19 – 20 female. 21 – 28 M. epaphus (23 – 28 upper side left, underside right), 21 – 22 M. epaphus pyrrha, male; 23 female from Porto Acre, Acre, Brazil; 24 female from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil; 25 M. epaphus epaphus, male from Belém, Pará, Brazil; 26 M. epaphus pyrrha, male from São Paulo de Olivença, Amazonas, Brazil; 27 – 28, M. epaphus pyrrha, males from Senador Guiomard, Acre, Brazil. 29 – 32 M. leucophrys, 29 – 30 male from Santa Rosa do Purus, Acre, Brazil; 31 – 32 female. Scale bar 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256291/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">Figs 21–22, 26–28</figureCitation>
), and observed a number of variable intermediate phenotypes between the 
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E05B7BEFD54FBB0" box="[581,659,1482,1505]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">sertata</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786E8DB7BDFCDEFBB3" box="[717,793,1481,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrrha">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E8DB7BDFCDEFBB3" box="[717,793,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">pyrrha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from a single locality, with identical morphology of the male genitalia. Therefore, we recognize 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786E1AB79AFC0BF857" authority="Stichel, 1910" authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1910" box="[602,972,1517,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="epaphus" status="syn. nov." subSpecies="sertata">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786E1AB79AFCF6F854" box="[602,817,1517,1542]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus sertata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="50364B3DB565DB786F78B799FC0BF857" author="Stichel" box="[824,972,1517,1542]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" refString="Stichel, H. (1910) Fam. Riodinidae. Allgemeines. Subfam. Riodininae. Genera Insectorum, 112 a, 1 - 238." type="book chapter" year="1910">Stichel, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="1DE057A5B565DB786F92B799FBFDF857" box="[978,1082,1517,1542]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786F92B799FBFDF857" bold="true" box="[978,1082,1517,1542]" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">syn. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
as a new junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB78693DB79AFE8BF87B" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="epaphus" subSpecies="pyrrha">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB78693DB79AFE8BF87B" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus pyrrha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB786EC5B466FCA3F87B" box="[645,868,1553,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="epaphus" subSpecies="pyrrha">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB786EC5B466FCA3F87B" box="[645,868,1553,1578]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">M. epaphus pyrrha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which occurs in the western Amazon basin, in relation to the nominative subspecies, only known from the northeast of the Amazon basin, needs further research. Due to distribution of 
<collectionCode id="52B6AE09B565DB786DD9B42EFE17F823" box="[409,464,1626,1650]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15690" name="California Academy of Sciences" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">CAS</collectionCode>
and morphology of the male genitalia, this species belongs to the “ 
<taxonomicName id="F3A74D4FB565DB78689CB42DFAF2F823" box="[1244,1333,1625,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Mesene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phareus">
<emphasis id="06D3EADEB565DB78689CB42DFAF2F823" box="[1244,1333,1625,1650]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="470">phareus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” species group.
</paragraph>
